      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen observing other animals and ourselves, we can reach some conclusions. For example, by noting that we developed counting systems at least 37,000 years ago, as evidenced by marks found on baboon bones (**Figure 1**) (<htcite0>), and by verifying that other animals do not perform such actions, we can conclude that no other species in the past did anything similar either. However, this conclusion deserves some reflection.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., et al.",
                     "page": "pp. 180 - 181",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img9\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img9', '0%')\"  class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Representation of baboon bone adorned with markings. This image, credited to Enrique Silván Pobes, is featured in the scholarly work of Francisco A. Gonzáles Redondo et al.<br />The original is available in ResearchNet (<htcite0>), and its inclusion here is made possible by the authorization of Doctor Francisco A. Gonzales Redondo.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., et al.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: What if it is found?</b><br /><br />When dealing with other species, if we claim that something never happened, we need to have sufficient information to avoid mistakes. Even so, as new research is conducted, new data may emerge and lead us to change our minds.<br /><br />Suppose a species different from our own did something we believed to be unique to human beings. How would you react to that discovery?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
